components.title: Section 4 - Detailed Ecological Risk Assessment Checklist

components.html: 1.1 Does the DERA identify who the major participants are in the risk assessment and state their qualifications?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.2 Does the DERA describe how the method(s) of assessment and the findings of any previous investigation(s) were used to design and carry out the current assessment?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.3 Does the DERA describe the extent to which any previous assessment(s) were/were not relied upon?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.4 If ministry preapprovals apply to the DERA, has all required preapproval documentation been provided with the risk assessment?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.5 Does the report make it clear what conditions are required (if any) for the instrument being applied for (e.g., Schedule B conditions for a Certificate of Compliance)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.6 Has field data relevant to the ecological risk assessment been provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 1.7 Has laboratory data relevant to the ecological risk assessment been provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.1 Have the objectives of the ecological risk assessment been documented? (See footnote 1)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.2 Were assessment and measurement endpoints for operative exposure pathways warranting further assessment defined? (See footnote 1)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.3 Were assessment and measurement endpoints linked to the risk assessment objectives? (See footnote 1)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.4 Were all current and reasonable potential future land, water and sediment uses identified in the problem formulation and considered in screening for chemical exceedances?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.5 Were assumptions associated with current and future land use documented and rationale provided (e.g., development scenario)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.6 Were potential contaminants of concern identified?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.7 Was a conceptual site model included?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.8 Were all relevant exposure pathways (direct and indirect) identified and considered?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.9 If the site was previously assessed using screening level risk assessment (SLRA) and if exposure pathways excluded under the SLRA were not considered in the DERA; were the assumptions upon which the pathways were excluded in the SLRA confirmed in the DERA? (See footnote 2)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.10 If statistics were used in the DERA, was a rationale provided for the statistical methods used?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.11 Was a rationale provided for any exclusion of contaminants that exceed applicable standards, criteria, or guidelines? (See footnote 3)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.12 Did a qualified professional visit and assess the site?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.13 Were receptors of potential concern identified based on commonly accepted risk assessment practice, including consideration of: ecological relevance, social importance, exposure potential and contaminant sensitivity? (See footnote 4)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.14 Was the site assessed for likely use by red and blue listed species?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.15 Were contaminant-pathway-receptor combinations that warranted further assessment clearly identified?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.16 If contaminant-pathway-receptor combinations were excluded from further assessment, was a rationale for the exclusion provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.17 If bioassays were used, was detailed rationale provided for the selection of the toxicity tests used, (e.g., consideration of: sensitivity of the organism to the potential contaminants of concern; potential confounding factors; taxonomic diversity, etc.)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.18 If the assessment of risk was based on several lines of evidence, was the approach used to evaluate individual lines of evidence and to integrate findings across lines of evidence documented? (See footnote 5)
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 2.19 Were future contaminant concentrations and potential contaminant degradation products considered?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.1 Was each contaminant-pathway-receptor combination identified for further assessment evaluated?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.2 Was each applicable land use scenario (current and future) evaluated?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.3 Was supporting rationale provided for methods used to estimate exposure point contaminant concentration(s)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.4 If a fate and transport model or other exposure model was used, were model equations provided and referenced?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.5 If an exposure model was used, were equations and the input data provided to support an independent quality assurance check for each exposure route in the risk assessment?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.6 Were all exposure model parameters defined and was rationale provided for all exposure model parameter values (with references where applicable)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.7 If an exposure model was used, was uncertainty regarding both: (a) the structure of the exposure model and (b) the parameter values used in the exposure model, considered in any interpretation of the results of the exposure modelling?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.8 If an exposure model was used, were the models results compared to, or calibrated to, empirical (i.e., measured data) to determine if the model adequately represents reality?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.9 For any models used, was a sensitivity analysis or a rationale for the absence of a sensitivity analysis provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 3.10 Were data quality objectives established for field parameters used in the risk assessment?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.1 If ecological surveys (e.g., plant, soil invertebrate, bird, fish, or benthic communities) were conducted, was the survey methodology used (including sampling locations and seasons) documented?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.2 If toxicity reference values (TRVs) were used, was a rationale for the selection and/or development of the TRVs provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.3 If TRVs were used, was the source of the TRVs referenced? If TRVs were developed de novo, was their derivation documented?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.4 If TRVs were used, was the toxicity endpoint associated with each TRV identified?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.5 Did the level of protection used in the DERA comply with the level specified in the ministry ecological risk assessment policy summary6 for the applicable land use or media?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.6 If risks were evaluated relative to: a reference site(s) or reference condition(s), was rationale for the selection of the reference site(s) or reference condition(s) provided? Were confounding variables (e.g., soil: texture, pH, grain size, depth etc.) addressed and considered in the evaluation?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.7 If site-specific toxicity testing was conducted, did the test method(s) used meet the quality standards of Environment Canada (See footnote 7), ASTM (See footnote 8) or another recognized government agency?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.8 If site-specific toxicity tests were conducted, did the tests include samples from the most contaminated area of the site?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.9 Were potential toxicological interactions (e.g., synergistic or antagonistic effects) between potential contaminants of concern discussed?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 4.10 Were up to date toxicity profiles provided for each potential contaminant of concern?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.1 Was sufficient detail provided for equations used to calculate numeric risk estimates so that it is clear how the estimates were derived?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.2 Was preference given to the use of hazard quotients in expressing numeric risk estimates?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.3 If hazard quotients were calculated, were they documented for each complete contaminant-receptor-pathway combination (as identified in the Problem Formulation)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.4 If hazard quotients were not calculated, was rationale provided for using a different approach (e.g., site observations or plotting exposure with dose-response data)?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.5 If an ecological hazard quotient exceeded unity, but the level of risk was considered acceptable, was a rationale provided?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.6 Were risks for all operative contaminant-receptor-pathways detailed in the problem formulation assessed and categorized as acceptable or unacceptable?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.7 Were the conclusions (i.e., risk characterization) consistent with the assessment endpoints?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 5.8 Does the risk assessment provide an explicit risk conclusion in regard to the significance of the ecological risk posed by the contamination at the site?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 6.1 Were uncertainties (e.g., measurement uncertainty, random variations, conceptual uncertainty and ignorance) explicitly evaluated and stated, including their implications on risk conclusions?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 6.2 If a weight-of-evidence approach was used, was preference given to assigning quantifiable, a priori weightings to weighted aspects of the DERA?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 6.3 If a weight-of-evidence approach was used, were the weight-of-evidence conclusions determined in a manner consistent with the approach laid out in the problem formulation?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html: 6.4 If a weight-of-evidence approach was used, were uncertainties associated with the use of the assigned weightings explicitly evaluated and stated, including their implications on risk conclusions?
components.label: Text/Images

components.html:
Footnotes

  1. Ecological risk assessment objectives and assessment and measurement endpoints are described in Science Advisory Board for Contaminated Sites in British Columbia, Report on: Detailed Ecological Risk Assessment (DERA) in British Columbia Technical Guidance, September, 2008.
  2. Where both SLRA and DRA are applied at a site, pathways screened using SLRA should be re-evaluated in the problem formulation stage of the DRA to confirm that the assumptions and conditions inherent in SLRA are satisfied at the site.
  3. Province of British Columbia. Environmental Management Act. BC Reg 375/96 Contaminated Sites Regulation Section 59 (2).
  4. Guidance on selecting receptors of potential concern can be found in Science Advisory Board for Contaminated Sites in British Columbia, Report on: Detailed Ecological Risk Assessment (DERA) in British Columbia Technical Guidance, September, 2008.
  5. Guidance on the use of weight-of-evidence evaluation under DERA can be found in Science Advisory Board for Contaminated Sites in British Columbia, Report on: Guidance for a Weight of Evidence Approach in Conducting Detailed Ecological Risk Assessments (DERA) in British Columbia, October, 2010.
  6. Ministry of Environment, lands and Parks. Tier 1 Ecological Risk Assessment Policy Decision Summary. Victoria, British Columbia. 1999.
  7. Environment Canada toxicity test protocols are available from the Environment Canada Biological Test Method Series website. Environment Canada. Ottawa, Ontario.
  8. ASTM toxicity testing protocols can be purchased through the ASTM Committee E47 on Biological Effects and Environmental Fate website. American Society for Testing and Materials International. Technical Committee E47 on Biological Effects and Environmental Fate.

components.title: Section 7 - Professional Statements and Signatures  To be completed by the Qualified Professional

components.html:
In accordance with Section 63 of the Contaminated Sites Regulation, I confirm that:

  1. The detailed ecological risk assessment for which this checklist is submitted has been performed in accordance with ministry approved methods, procedures, guidance and standards of professional practice;
  2. The responses provided in this Detailed Ecological Risk Assessment Checklist are true and accurate based on current knowledge as of the date completed; and
  3. I have demonstrable experience in conducting ecological risk assessments and in conducting investigations of the type used to prepare the detailed ecological risk assessment for which this checklist is submitted.
components.label: Text/Images
